Uniform Random Variables are used where each outcome of an event is equally probable. For <math>p_{U}(u) = P(U \leq u)</math> where <math>U\,</math> is some <math>[a,b]\,</math>-Uniform Random Variable, <math>p_{U}(u)\,</math> will always be zero unless <math>(a \leq u \leq b)</math>. When <math>(a \leq u \leq b)</math>, then <math>p_{U}(u) = \frac{1}{b - a}</math>.
==Equations== {| |- | align="right" | <math>\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f_{X}(x)\delta x</math> | align="left" | <math> = 1\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>f_{X}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = \begin{cases} \frac{1}{b - a}& a < x < b\\ 0& \mbox{else}\\ \end{cases}</math> |- | align="right" | <math>F_{X}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = \begin{cases} 0& x < a\\ \frac{x - a}{b - a}& a \leq x < b\\ 1& x \geq b\\ \end{cases}</math> |- | align="right" | <math>h_{X}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = ???\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>M_{X}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = \frac{e^{xb}-e^{xa}}{x\left(b-a\right)}</math> |}
==Links== * [[w:Uniform_distribution_%28continuous%29|The Continuous Uniform Distribution]] * [[w:Uniform_distribution_%28discrete%29|The Discrete Uniform Distribution]]
{{BookCat}}

The basic idea behind independence is that if your random variables (or vectors) are independent then the combination of several of these random variable/vectors <math>\left(P\left(X_{1} \leq x_{1}, ..., X_{d} \leq x_{d}\right)\right)</math> can be multiplied together.
Given <math>T_{1}, T_{2}\,</math> are independent <math>\lambda\,\mbox{-Exponential}</math> random variables, then <math>E\left[T_{1} + T_{2}\right] = E\left[2T_{1}\right] = E\left[2T_{2}\right]</math>. But <math>\mbox{Var}\left(T_{1} + T_{2}\right) < \mbox{Var}\left(2T_{1}\right)</math>. This is because <math>\mbox{Var}\left(T_{1} + T_{2}\right) = \mbox{Var}\left(T_{1}\right) + \mbox{Var}\left(T_{2}\right) = 2\mbox{Var}\left(T_{1}\right)</math> by independence, whereas <math>\mbox{Var}\left(2T_{1}\right) = 2^{2}\cdot\mbox{Var}\left(T_{1}\right)</math>.
See the equations section for some more examples.
==Equations== {| |- | align="right" | <math>P\left(X_{1} \leq x_{1}, ..., X_{d} \leq x_{d}\right)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = P\left(X_{1} \leq x_{1}\right) \cdots P\left(X_{d} \leq x_{d}\right)\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>F_{X_{1},X_{2},...X_{d}}(x_{1...d})\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = F_{X_{1}}(x_{1}) \cdots F_{X_{d}}(x_{d})\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>f_{X_{1},X_{2},...X_{d}}(x_{1...d})\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = f_{X_{1}}(x_{1}) \cdots f_{X_{d}}(x_{d})\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>E\left[X_{1}\cdot X_{2}\cdots X_{d}\right]\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = E\left[X_{1}\right] \cdots E\left[X_{d}\right]\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>E\left[g_{1}\left(X_{1}\right)\cdot g_{2}\left(X_{2}\right)\cdots g_{d}\left(X_{d}\right)\right]\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = E\left[g_{1}\left(X_{1}\right)\right] \cdots E\left[g_{d}\left(X_{d}\right)\right]\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>M_{X_{1}+...+X_{d}}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = M_{X_{1}}(x) \cdots M_{X_{1}}(x)\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>F_{XY}(x,y)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = ???\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>f_{XY}(x,y)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = ???\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>F_{X|Y}(x|y)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = ???\,</math> |- | align="right" | <math>F_{X+Y}(x)\,</math> | align="left" | <math> = P\left(X + Y \leq x\right)\,</math> |}
{{BookCat}}

