==Pronunciation of finals== {| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 95%" !'''Pinyin'''||'''[[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]'''||'''Final-only form'''||'''Explanation''' |- ||''a''|| {{IPA|[a]}} ||'''a'''|| if ending a syllable, then as in "f'''a'''ther" |- ||''o''|| {{IPA|[ɔ]}} ||(n/a)|| plain continental ''''or''''. Only used in certain interjections. |- ||''e''|| {{IPA|[ɤ]}}, {{IPA|[ə]}} ||'''e'''|| when occurring at the end of a syllable and not in the combinations of ie, üe, ue, then a backward, unrounded vowel, which can be formed by first pronouncing a plain continental "o" ([[w:Australian English|AuE]] and [[w:New Zealand English|NZE]] l'''aw''') and then spreading the lips without changing the position of the tongue. That same sound is also similar to English "d'''uh'''", but not as open. Many unstressed syllables in Chinese use the [[w:schwa|schwa]] (ide'''a'''), and this is also written as ''e''. |- ||''ê''|| {{IPA|[ɛ]}} ||(n/a)|| as in "b'''e'''t". Only used in certain interjections. |- ||''ai''|| {{IPA|[aɪ̯]}} ||'''ai'''|| like English "eye", but a bit lighter |- ||''ei''|| {{IPA|[eɪ̯]}} ||'''ei'''|| as in "h'''ey'''" |- ||''ao''|| {{IPA|[ɑʊ̯]}} ||'''ao'''|| approximately as in "c'''ow'''"; the ''a'' is much more audible than the ''o'' |- ||''ou''|| {{IPA|[oʊ̯]}} ||'''ou'''|| as in "s'''o'''", "d'''ough'''" |- ||''an''|| {{IPA|[an]}} ||'''an'''|| starts with plain continental "a" ([[w:Australian English|AuE]] and [[w:New Zealand English|NZE]] b'''u'''d) and ends with "n"; as in "st'''un'''", "f'''un'''" |- ||''en''|| {{IPA|[ən]}} ||'''en'''|| as in "tak'''en'''" |- ||''ang''|| {{IPA|[ɑŋ]}} ||'''ang'''|| as in German ''Angst'', including the English loan word ''angst'' (starts with the vowel sound in f'''a'''ther and ends in the [[w:velar nasal| velar nasal]]; as in "fl'''ung'''", "d'''ung'''", "y'''oung'''";like s'''ong''' in American English) |- ||''eng''|| {{IPA|[əŋ]}} ||'''eng'''||like ''e'' in ''en'' above but with ng added to it at the back |- ||''er''|| {{IPA|[ɑɻ]}} ||'''er'''|| like ''ar'' (exists only on own, or as last part of final in combination with others- see bottom of list) |- ||''i''|| {{IPA|[i]}} ||'''yi'''|| like English "ee", except when preceded by "c", "ch", "r", "s", "sh", "z" or "zh"; in these cases it should be pronounced as a natural extension of those sounds in the same position, but slightly more open to allow for a clear-sounding vowel to pass through |- || ''ia'' || {{IPA|[i̯a]}} ||'''ya'''|| as '''i''' + '''a'''; like English "'''ya'''rd" or the name "'''ia'''go" |- || ''io'' || {{IPA|[iou]}} ||(n/a)|| as '''i''' + '''o'''; like English slang "'''yo'''"; (only exists as a final-only interjection) |- ||''ie''|| {{IPA|[i̯ɛ]}} ||'''ye'''|| as '''i''' + '''ê'''; but is very short; ''e'' (pronounced like ''ê'') is pronounced longer and carries the main stress (similar to the initial sound '''ye''' in '''yet''') |- || ''iai'' || {{IPA|[iɑi]}} ||'''yai'''|| as '''i''' + '''ai'''; like "'''yi'''" in "'''yikes'''"; (only exists as final-only form "'''yai'''") |- ||''iao''|| {{IPA|[i̯ɑʊ̯]}} ||'''yao'''|| as '''i''' + '''ao''' |- ||''iu''|| {{IPA|[i̯oʊ̯]}} ||'''you'''|| as '''i''' + '''ou''' |- ||''ian''|| {{IPA|[i̯ɛn]}} ||'''yan'''|| as '''i''' + '''an'''; like English '''yen''' |- ||''in''|| {{IPA|[in]}} ||'''yin'''|| as '''i''' + '''en'''; as in the English word "in"; |- ||''iang''|| {{IPA|[i̯ɑŋ]}} ||'''yang'''|| as '''i''' + '''ang''' |- ||''ing''|| {{IPA|[iŋ]}} ||'''ying'''|| as '''i''' + '''eng''' |- ||''u''|| {{IPA|[u]}} ||'''wu'''|| like English "oo", except in xu and yu, where it is pronounced as u |- ||''ua''|| {{IPA |[u̯a]}} ||'''wa'''|| as '''u''' + '''a''' |- ||''uo'', ''o''|| {{IPA|[u̯ɔ]}} ||'''wo'''|| as '''u''' + '''o''' (as '''o''' after initials b, p, m and f); the ''o'' is pronounced shorter and lighter than in the ''o'' final |- ||''uai''|| {{IPA|[u̯aɪ̯]}} ||'''wai'''|| as '''u''' + '''ai''' |- ||''ui''|| {{IPA|[u̯eɪ̯]}} ||'''wei'''|| as '''u''' + '''ei'''; here, the ''i'' is pronounced like ''ei'' |- ||''uan''|| {{IPA|[u̯an]}} ||'''wan'''|| as '''u''' + '''an''' |- ||''un''|| {{IPA|[u̯ən]}} ||'''wen'''|| as '''u''' + '''en'''; like the ''on'' in the English ''won'' |- ||''uang''|| {{IPA|[u̯ɑŋ]}} ||'''wang'''|| as '''u''' + '''ang'''; like the ''ang'' in English ''angst'' or ''anger'' |- ||''ong''|| {{IPA|[ʊŋ]}}, {{IPA|[u̯əŋ]}} ||'''weng'''|| as '''u''' + '''eng'''; starts with the vowel sound in b'''oo'''k and ends with the velar nasal sound in si'''ng''' |- ||''ü''|| {{IPA|[y]}} ||'''yu'''|| as in German "'''ü'''ben" or French "l'''u'''ne" (To get this sound, say "ee" with rounded lips) |- ||''üe''|| {{IPA|[y̯œ]}} ||'''yue'''|| as '''ü''' + '''ê'''; the ''ü'' is short and light |- ||''üan''|| {{IPA|[y̯ɛn]}} ||'''yuan'''|| as '''ü''' + '''an'''; |- ||''ün''|| {{IPA|[yn]}} ||'''yun'''|| as '''ü''' + '''en'''; |- ||''iong''|| {{IPA|[i̯ʊŋ]}} ||'''yong'''|| as '''ü''' + '''eng'''; |}
{| class="wikitable" style="font-size: 95%" |- ! colspan=3 | Finals that are a combination of finals above + '''er''' final |- !'''Pinyin'''||'''[[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]'''||'''Explanation''' |- | e'r || {{IPA|[ɤɻ]}} || as '''e''' + '''er''' (not to be confused with ''er'' final on its own- this form only exists with an initial character before it) |- | air, anr || {{IPA|[ɑɻ]}} || as '''ai''' + '''er''', '''an''' + '''er''' |- | aor || {{IPA|[ɑʊ̯ɻ]}} || as '''ao''' + '''er''' |- | our || {{IPA|[oʊ̯ɻ]}} || as '''ou''' + '''er''' |- | angr || {{IPA|[ɑŋɻ]}} || as '''ang''' + '''er''' |- | iar, ianr || {{IPA|[i̯ɑɻ]}} || as '''ia''' + '''er''', '''ian''' + '''er''' |- | inr, ir || {{IPA|[i̯əɻ]}} || as '''in''' + '''er''', '''i''' + '''er''' |- | ingr || {{IPA|[i̯əŋɻ]}} || as '''ing''' + '''er''' |- | ur || {{IPA|[uɻ]}} || as '''u''' + '''er''' |- | uor || {{IPA|[u̯ɔɻ]}} || as '''uo''' + '''er''' |- | uir || {{IPA|[u̯əɻ]}} || as '''ui''' + '''er''' |- | ongr || {{IPA|[ʊŋɻ]}} || as '''ong''' + '''er''' |- | ür || {{IPA|[y̯əɻ]}} || as '''ü''' + '''er''' |}
