Let <math>z</math> and <math>w</math> be complex numbers. Since we have: :{| |- |<math>|z+w|^2 \,</math> |<math> = (z+w) \overline {(z+w)} = (z + w)(\bar z + \bar w)</math> |- | |<math>=|z|^2 + z \bar w + \overline { z \bar w } + |w|^2</math> |- | |<math>=|z|^2 + 2\mbox{Re }(z \bar w) + |w|^2</math> |- | |<math>\le |z|^2 + 2|z||w| + |w|^2</math> |- | |<math>= (|z| + |w|)^2 \,</math> |} the triangular inequality follows after taking the square root of both sides. Note here we used the properties: :<math>\mbox{ Re}(z) \le |z|</math>, <math>|z| = |\bar z|</math> and <math>z + \bar z = 2\mbox{Re }(z)</math>.
Also, the induction shows: :<math>\left | \sum_1^n z_k \right | \le \sum_1^n |z_k|</math>
{{BookCat}}

{{fruit}}

Hawberries are berries known to grow on Manitoulin Island thanks to its distinctive alkaline soil. During the pioneer days, white settlers ate these berries during the winter as the only remaining food supply. People who saw these settlers collecting the berries started to call them "haweaters". People born on the island are now called "haweaters".

A hawberry is small and oblong, similar in size and shape to a small olive or grape. It is red in colour when ripe and grows on bushes. Varying from a shrub to a small tree, hawberries develop in groups of 2-3 along smaller branches. Berries delicate in taste and are pulpy with multiple seeds.

The hawberry is edible, but is commonly made into jellies, jams, and syrups rather than eaten whole. Some people say pick them when they are bright red in color, and others say to wait until they are black and are about to fall apart.

{{wikipedia|Hawberry}}

YafRay ('''Y'''et '''A'''nother '''F'''ree '''Ray'''tracer) is an open source ray tracing program available under the the LGPL license. It enables the creation of images and animations to a photo-realistic quality. 

Yafray was developed in C++ and can be ported to a number of operating systems including Linux, Windows (9x, 2000 and XP), Mac OSX and Irix. 

It has a number of rendering features including: global illumination, skydome illumination, caustics, depth of field and blurry reflections.

