This is a list of all the mathematical symbols used in this book.
<!--Use this template for symbol definitions {{Mathematical Proof/symbol||}}. The first argument is the symbol and the second is its definition.-->

{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>[a,b]</math>|Interval notation. Signifies the set of all numbers between a and b}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>\lor</math>|A logical "or" connector.  A truth statement whose truth value is true if either of the two given statements is true and false if they are both false.  <math>P\lor Q</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>\land</math>|A logical "and" connector.  A truth statement whose truth value is true only if both of the two given statements is true and false otherwise. <math>P\land Q</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>\lnot</math>|A logical "not" unary operator.  A truth statement whose value is opposite of the given statement.  <math> \lnot P</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<nowiki>{ }</nowiki>|Set delimiters.  A set may be defined explicitly (e.g. <math> A = \{1,2,3,4\}</math>), or pseudo-explicitly by giving a pattern (e.g. <math> B = \{2,4,6,8,\ldots\}</math>.  It may also be defined with a given rule (e.g. <math> C = \{ x | P(x)\}</math>, the set of all ''x'' such that ''P(x)'' is true).}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>\in</math>|The "element of" binary operator.  This shows element inclusion in a set.  If ''x'' is an element of ''A'' we write <math> x\in A.</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math>\subset</math>|The "set inclusion" or "subset" binary operator.  If all the elements of ''A'' are in ''B'', then we say that ''A'' is a subset of ''B'' and write <math>A\subset B.</math>  Note that in this book, <math>A\subset B</math> when <math> A=B.</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math> \cup </math>|The union of two sets.  A set containing all elements of two given sets.  <math>A\cup B = \{x|(x\in A) \lor (x\in B)\}.</math>}}
{{Mathematical Proof/symbol|<math> \cap </math>|The intersection of two sets.  A set containing all the elements that are in both of two given sets.  <math>A\cap B = \{x|(x\in A)\land (x\in B)\}.</math>}}

